ent Asbury Park residents, Daniel Wolff uncovers the history of how this Jersey shore resort town came to epitomize both the promises of the American dream and the tragic consequences when those promises are broken. Hailed by The New York Times as a “wonderfully evocative…grand, sad story” when first published in 2006, this revised and expanded edition considers how Asbury Park has changed in the twenty-first century, experiencing both gentrification and new forms of segregation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArtszNew JerseyzAsbury ParkxHistory. 0aRock groupszNew JerseyzAsbury ParkxHistory. 0aRock musiczNew JerseyzAsbury ParkxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBruce Springsteen, Asbury Park, New Jersey, seaside, working-class, music history, American Dream, NJ, The Promise Land, boardwalk town, small town, Greetings from Asbury Park, Frank Sinatra, gentrification, amusement park, resort town, racial issues, urban renewal, political corruption, American values, racial tensions, boom towns, Asbury Part Race Riots, July 1970, protest, Stone Pony, American life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882043240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978820432423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978820432/original  a978-3-11-076647-9  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK